===subject:In Agreement with Jodi
===from:Jordan Berkow
===date:Wed Oct 15 21:00:41 2003
===message:I also agree with Jodi that this was a period in our history where African Americans celebrated their racial differences.  I also believe that this was a time when they began to define their own sub-culture in the U.S.  Since this was a time when African Americans weren’t socially accepted into the white culture, this was the time for the “New Negro” to be born.<br><br>  
   In my opinion the “New Negro” was a person who separated him or herself from how things were in the past, and began to publicize and work for recognition and status.  By becoming artists, poets, and musicians, the African American community began to define and create their own ideals and traditions.  The “New Negro” didn’t sit back and allow society to run over them.  The mass movement from the Southern States to New York City was one example of coming together and making a place in the industrial socities.<br><br>
   The Harlem Renaissance began the time when African Americans could celebrate their skills and talents and also portray them to the public.  This was the small stepping stone to the Civil Rights movement.  Until that time though, African Americans would still have to deal with segregation and suppression in many areas.  In many ways though, the Harlem Renaissance began to bring forth individuals who would fight politically for true equal freedoms.

=========yorg=========
