===subject:Harlem Renaissance
===from:reply to Jodi
===date:Fri Oct 17 13:17:34 2003
===message:I agree that the “New Negro” was “alone in their struggles to gain strength in America”, because it is basically the same way today.  When the NAACP was first begun, many white people supported it.  However, when black people made it clear that they would not be content to “stay in their place”, membership by white people declined drastically.  This proves that black people were truly alone in their struggle, because no one but another black person could really understand what the struggle for equal rights was  about and see the desperate need for an organization like the NAACP, even in the year 2003, (nearly 100 years later), showing that not much changes with time and struggle.
